    <h1 class="page-title">Large-scale environments of star-forming active galactic nuclei</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Mountrichas et al. (2026)</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Paper</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Authors:</th>
          <td>G. Mountrichas, F. J. Carrera, F. Shankar, A. Georgakakis</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>arXiv / DOI:</th>
          <td><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11169">arXiv:2603.11169</a> — <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2603.11169">DOI</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Date:</th>
          <td>2026-03-11 (v1) — A&A accepted</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Analysis:</th>
          <td><a href="/data/papers/mountrichas2026_agn_environments.md">Paper analysis (markdown)</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Related concepts:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/dark_matter_halos" text="Dark matter halos" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/agn_environment" text="AGN environment" />
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p><strong>Abstract (short)</strong> — Mountrichas et al. combine XXL and Stripe82X X-ray AGN samples (427 broad-line AGN at 0.5&lt;z&lt;1.2; >20,000 galaxies) to measure AGN large-scale environments via AGN–galaxy cross-correlation and a multivariate nearest-neighbour matching scheme. They find typical AGN halo masses of log(M_DMH/h^{-1}M_☉) ≃ 13 and no significant dependence of halo mass on M_BH, λ_Edd, or L_X within their uncertainties.</p>

    <h2 id="key-findings">Key findings</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        Typical halo mass for X-ray BLAGN is group-scale (log(M_DMH/h^{-1}M_☉) ≃ 13).  
        <small><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.11169">(Mountrichas et al. 2026, arXiv:2603.11169)</a></small>
      </li>
      <li>
        No statistically significant variation of halo mass with black-hole mass, Eddington ratio, or X-ray luminosity after controlling for host-galaxy properties using nearest-neighbour matching.  
        <small>(Mountrichas+2026)</small>
      </li>
      <li>
        Interpretation: AGN short-term accretion and long-term BH growth are primarily regulated by internal host-galaxy processes; large-scale environment supplies boundary conditions (gas reservoir, duty cycle).  
        <small>(Mountrichas+2026)</small>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="methods">Methods</h2>
    <p>The authors infer dark-matter halo masses by measuring AGN–galaxy cross-correlation functions and converting clustering amplitude (bias) to halo mass using standard halo-bias relations. They control for host properties with a multivariate nearest-neighbour matching algorithm so that comparisons across bins of M_BH, λ_Edd and L_X are performed under similar host-galaxy distributions.</p>

    <h2 id="limitations">Limitations</h2>
    <p>Results apply to X-ray selected, broad-line AGN at 0.5&lt;z&lt;1.2. The study does not directly constrain obscured AGN, very low-luminosity AGN, or other redshift ranges; selection effects and sample size limit sensitivity to subtle environmental trends.</p>

